    <item>
      <title>Why using default_scope is a bad idea</title>
      <link>blog url/ruby/rails/best-practices/why-using-default-scope-is-a-bad-idea.html</link>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;code&gt;default_scope&lt;/code&gt; is a method provided by ActiveRecord, which allows you to set
a default scope (as its name implies) for all operations done on a given model.
It can be useful for allowing soft-deletion in your models, by having a
&lt;code&gt;deleted_on&lt;/code&gt; column on your model and setting the default scope to
&lt;code&gt;deleted_on: nil&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
      <pubDate>Mon, 20 Jul 2015 06:55:00 -0300</pubDate>
      <dc:date>2015-07-20T06:55:00-03:00</dc:date>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Mercado Pago Security Hole</title>
      <link>blog url/security/mercado-pago-security-vulnerability.html</link>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;On April 17th we discovered a security vulnerability in the &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.mercadopago.com.ar/developers/en/api-docs/&quot;&gt;Mercado Pago API&lt;/a&gt;. Before disclosing this information, we contacted &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.mercadolibre.com/&quot;&gt;Mercado Libre&lt;/a&gt; and sent them a detailed report of the security hole and how to reproduce it.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The vulnerability allowed anyone to get an access token without using the right secret for an account.&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
      <pubDate>Tue, 14 Jul 2015 20:29:00 -0300</pubDate>
      <dc:date>2015-07-14T20:29:00-03:00</dc:date>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>The Lean Startup Way</title>
      <link>blog url/lean-startup/the-lean-startup-way.html</link>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;At &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ombulabs.com&quot;&gt;OmbuLabs&lt;/a&gt; we like to split our time working on our own products, client projects, and open source code. We have embraced the Lean Startup methodology not only for our own products but also for our client projects.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It is easier to apply the methodology to our own products than to our client projects. With our products, we decide what goals we want to reach and what experiments we are going to run to validate our hypotheses.&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
      <pubDate>Tue, 30 Jun 2015 20:29:00 -0300</pubDate>
      <dc:date>2015-06-30T20:29:00-03:00</dc:date>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>How to Git push with blocked ports</title>
      <link>blog url/git/github/how-to-git-push-with-blocked-ports.html</link>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Often times I find myself working out of a coffee shop with a &lt;strong&gt;terrible Internet connection&lt;/strong&gt;. We have a nice office at &lt;a href=&quot;https://es.foursquare.com/v/ombushop-hq/52f0e47311d25da04d101b62&quot;&gt;OmbuLabs&lt;/a&gt; but there is still that &lt;em&gt;Je ne sais quoi&lt;/em&gt; at coffee shops.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The cool thing about &lt;a href=&quot;https://git-scm.com/&quot;&gt;Git&lt;/a&gt; is that you can &lt;code&gt;git commit&lt;/code&gt; all your changes while enjoying a cup of coffee and &lt;code&gt;git push&lt;/code&gt; later (when you&amp;#39;re back at home with a decent connection)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;But what if you want to &lt;code&gt;git push&lt;/code&gt; from the coffee shop? Sometimes the only ports that are open are port 80 (HTTP) and 443 (HTTPS).&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
      <pubDate>Sun, 28 Jun 2015 15:29:00 -0300</pubDate>
      <dc:date>2015-06-28T15:29:00-03:00</dc:date>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Our Definition of &quot;Done&quot;</title>
      <link>blog url/software-development/software-quality/our-definition-of-done.html</link>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Quality should be present in everything you do, but it should be balanced with the time you spend working on a feature. Does it feel like you&amp;#39;ve been working on this feature for a &lt;strong&gt;really long time&lt;/strong&gt;? Maybe you have. Is it &amp;quot;done&amp;quot;?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;That is a tough question, so I&amp;#39;ll write down &lt;em&gt;our definition of done&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
      <pubDate>Thu, 18 Jun 2015 08:37:00 -0300</pubDate>
      <dc:date>2015-06-18T08:37:00-03:00</dc:date>
    </item>
